description: From Middle English store, stoure, storre, from Anglo-Norman stor, estore, estorr, estoer, and Old French estour, estor, from Latin īnstaurō.

entries.meaning: A place where items may be accumulated or routinely kept.
examples: This building used to be a store for old tires.

entries.meaning: (mainly North American) A place where items may be purchased; a shop.
examples: I need to get some milk from the grocery store.
The main store of 1000 36-bit words seemed large at the time.

entries.meaning: A great quantity or number; abundance.
A head of store cattle (feeder cattle to be sold to others for finishing); a store cattle beast.

verbs.description: store (third-person singular simple present stores, present participle storing, simple past and past participle stored)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To keep (something) while not in use, generally in a place meant for that purpose.
examples: I'll store these books in the attic.
The cabinets store all the food the mice would like.

entries.meaning: Have the capacity and capability to contain.
examples: They sell boxes that store 24 mason jars.

entries.meaning: (transitive, computing) To write (something) into memory or registers.
examples: This operation stores the result on the stack.
